{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"855c0b0f-c0bf-4c69-9cc7-ebcc10299eda","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a trace (e.g., 30 seconds of CPU profiling):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, you can download `dotnet-trace` as a [standalone tool](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#install).\n- For richer data (GC, exceptions, etc.), use `--profile gc-verbose` or `--providers` with custom EventPipe providers.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a good quick first look before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7fd2341e-c2d2-493e-afa6-23d1c04a97c5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"AC0B:271D55:1363D09:15C9FA4:6A066FE5"},"id":"57fdf838-5dea-408b-beba-8888f0e1a9ef","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:59:28.230Z","parentId":"6b1e258e-632d-4a2a-aeb9-395de47b9624"}
